Note: ===================================================================
Note: LATEX SEMANTIC ANALYZER
Note: ===================================================================
Note: Semantic analysis for LaTeX document preparation system. Handles
Note: document structure validation, package compatibility, reference
Note: resolution, citation validation, and academic document best practices.

Note: Part of the Translation System
Note: Location: compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/latex/latex_semantic.runa
Note: ===================================================================

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/latex/latex_lexer.runa" as Lexer
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/latex/latex_parser.runa" as Parser
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_primitive.runa" as StringPrim
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/dictionary.runa" as Dict

Note: ===================================================================
Note: SEMANTIC ANALYZER STRUCTURE
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
The LaTeX semantic analyzer tracks every named entity in a document:
the class declaration, loaded packages, defined commands/environments,
labels and references, citations and bibliography, counters, custom
newcommand/newenvironment definitions, included files, graphics,
tables, figures, equations, and sections. Five additional fields
collect cross-cutting validation results (undefined refs/cites, unused
labels, orphaned figures, package conflicts, encoding issues) and
three error/warning lists support the diagnostic interface. The flat
fanout matches LaTeX's diverse namespace requirements.
@End Reasoning
Type called "LaTeXSemanticAnalyzer":
    document_class as Integer
    packages as Integer
    commands as Integer
    environments as Integer
    labels as Integer
    references as Integer
    citations as Integer
    bibliography as Integer
    counters as Integer
    newcommands as Integer
    newenvironments as Integer
    includes as Integer
    inputs as Integer
    graphics as Integer
    tables as Integer
    figures as Integer
    equations as Integer
    sections as Integer
    document_structure as Integer
    package_dependencies as Integer
    undefined_references as Integer
    undefined_citations as Integer
    unused_labels as Integer
    orphaned_figures as Integer
    package_conflicts as Integer
    encoding_issues as Integer
    validation_errors as Integer
    validation_warnings as Integer
    style_warnings as Integer
    error_message as Integer
    has_error as Integer
End Type

Note: ===================================================================
Note: ANALYZER CREATION
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Allocates 248 bytes for the 31-slot analyzer struct then creates
the 28 collection registries (a mix of List and Dict) and writes
them into the struct's pointer fields. Each registry is eagerly
allocated even when most LaTeX documents only touch a handful;
the trade-off is a small fixed allocation cost vs. avoiding null
checks in every collector and validator below.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocate the 248-byte block. Create the registries: 17 Lists for
ordered sequences (packages, references, citations, bibliography,
includes, inputs, graphics, tables, figures, equations, sections,
document_structure, plus 6 diagnostic lists), 6 Dicts for
keyed lookups (commands, environments, labels, counters,
newcommands, newenvironments, package_dependencies). Write each
pointer to its offset (0-240 in 8-byte strides). error_message
and has_error initialized to 0.
@End Implementation
Process called "create_latex_semantic_analyzer" returns Integer:
    Note: Create LaTeX semantic analyzer for document validation

    Let analyzer_size be 248
    Let analyzer be proc allocate from Layout with analyzer_size

    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let packages be proc create from List
    Let commands be proc create from Dict
    Let environments be proc create from Dict
    Let labels be proc create from Dict
    Let references be proc create from List
    Let citations be proc create from List
    Let bibliography be proc create from List
    Let counters be proc create from Dict
    Let newcommands be proc create from Dict
    Let newenvironments be proc create from Dict
    Let includes be proc create from List
    Let inputs be proc create from List
    Let graphics be proc create from List
    Let tables be proc create from List
    Let figures be proc create from List
    Let equations be proc create from List
    Let sections be proc create from List
    Let document_structure be proc create from List
    Let package_dependencies be proc create from Dict
    Let undefined_references be proc create from List
    Let undefined_citations be proc create from List
    Let unused_labels be proc create from List
    Let orphaned_figures be proc create from List
    Let package_conflicts be proc create from List
    Let encoding_issues be proc create from List
    Let validation_errors be proc create from List
    Let validation_warnings be proc create from List
    Let style_warnings be proc create from List

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 0, 0  Note: document_class
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 8, packages
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 16, commands
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 24, environments
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 32, labels
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 40, references
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 48, citations
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 56, bibliography
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 64, counters
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 72, newcommands
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 80, newenvironments
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 88, includes
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 96, inputs
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 104, graphics
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 112, tables
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 120, figures
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 128, equations
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 136, sections
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 144, document_structure
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 152, package_dependencies
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 160, undefined_references
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 168, undefined_citations
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 176, unused_labels
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 184, orphaned_figures
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 192, package_conflicts
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 200, encoding_issues
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 208, validation_errors
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 216, validation_warnings
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 224, style_warnings
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 232, 0  Note: error_message
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 240, 0  Note: has_error

    Return analyzer
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: MAIN ANALYSIS ENTRY POINT
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Six-phase pipeline driving the full document analysis. The phase
ordering is significant: preamble collection must complete before
body collection (so package availability is known when validating
body elements); collection must complete before validation (so the
cross-reference set is complete); reference resolution must follow
structure validation (so we don't dangle on documents with broken
hierarchies); package validation runs after refs so package-defined
labels are seen.
@End Reasoning
Process called "analyze_latex_document" takes analyzer as Integer, latex_ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Perform complete semantic analysis on LaTeX document

    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If latex_ast is equal to 0:
        proc set_latex_semantic_error with analyzer, "Null LaTeX AST"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Phase 1: Collect document class and packages
    proc collect_latex_preamble with analyzer, latex_ast

    Note: Phase 2: Collect document structure and elements
    proc collect_latex_document_elements with analyzer, latex_ast

    Note: Phase 3: Validate document structure
    proc validate_latex_document_structure with analyzer

    Note: Phase 4: Resolve references and citations
    proc resolve_latex_references with analyzer

    Note: Phase 5: Validate package compatibility
    proc validate_latex_packages with analyzer

    Note: Phase 6: Check academic document conventions
    proc validate_latex_academic_conventions with analyzer

    Let has_error be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 240
    If has_error is equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: PREAMBLE COLLECTION
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Walks every element between \documentclass and \begin{document}.
Match-dispatch on the element's command name: documentclass and
usepackage feed the foundational registries; newcommand /
newenvironment populate the user-macro tables for later expansion
checks; include/input record file dependencies. Unknown preamble
commands are silently skipped (LaTeX preambles are highly
extensible).
@End Reasoning
Process called "collect_latex_preamble" takes analyzer as Integer, latex_ast as Integer:
    Note: Collect document class and package declarations

    Let preamble_elements be proc get_latex_preamble with latex_ast
    Let element_count be proc size from List with preamble_elements
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than element_count:
        Let element be proc get from List with preamble_elements, i
        Let element_type be proc get_latex_element_type with element

        Match element_type:
            When "documentclass":
                proc collect_latex_documentclass with analyzer, element
            When "usepackage":
                proc collect_latex_usepackage with analyzer, element
            When "newcommand":
                proc collect_latex_newcommand with analyzer, element
            When "newenvironment":
                proc collect_latex_newenvironment with analyzer, element
            When "include":
                proc collect_latex_include with analyzer, element
            When "input":
                proc collect_latex_input with analyzer, element
            Otherwise:
                Note: Other preamble elements can be processed here
        End Match

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
\documentclass{class}[options] - the document class controls page
geometry, section availability, and other foundational settings.
We write the class node pointer at offset 0 (the only single-valued
field in the analyzer). validate_document_class_structure later
checks that exactly one documentclass appeared.
@End Reasoning
Process called "collect_latex_documentclass" takes analyzer as Integer, documentclass_element as Integer:
    Note: Collect document class specification

    @Reasoning:
    Register document class with options for structure validation and
    feature compatibility checking. Document class determines available
    sectioning commands, page layout, and document structure rules.
    @End Reasoning

    Let class_name be proc get_latex_documentclass_name with documentclass_element
    Let class_options be proc get_latex_documentclass_options with documentclass_element

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 0, documentclass_element

    Note: Validate document class
    proc validate_latex_documentclass with analyzer, class_name, class_options
End Process

@Reasoning:
\usepackage{name}[options] - appends to the packages list at
offset 8. Order matters because LaTeX packages can conflict based
on load order (one package patches another's commands); we
preserve source order so check_package_load_order can flag known
problematic sequences.
@End Reasoning
Process called "collect_latex_usepackage" takes analyzer as Integer, usepackage_element as Integer:
    Note: Collect package inclusion

    @Reasoning:
    Register package with options for compatibility checking and dependency
    analysis. Packages provide additional functionality and may have
    conflicts or specific loading order requirements.
    @End Reasoning

    Let package_name be proc get_latex_package_name with usepackage_element
    Let package_options be proc get_latex_package_options with usepackage_element

    Let packages be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 8
    proc add from List with packages, usepackage_element

    Note: Track package dependencies
    Let package_dependencies be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 152
    Let dependencies be proc get_latex_package_dependencies with package_name
    proc set from Dict with package_dependencies, package_name, dependencies

    Note: Check for known package conflicts
    proc check_latex_package_conflicts with analyzer, package_name
End Process

@Reasoning:
\newcommand{\name}[args]{body} - user-defined macros. We register
each in the newcommands Dict keyed by name. This dict feeds the
later macro-expansion verifier which checks that uses of \name
appear after their declaration and match the argument count.
@End Reasoning
Process called "collect_latex_newcommand" takes analyzer as Integer, newcommand_element as Integer:
    Note: Collect user-defined command

    @Reasoning:
    Register custom commands for command validation and usage checking.
    User-defined commands extend LaTeX functionality and must be validated
    for proper definition and usage.
    @End Reasoning

    Let command_name be proc get_latex_newcommand_name with newcommand_element
    Let command_definition be proc get_latex_newcommand_definition with newcommand_element

    Let newcommands be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 72
    proc set from Dict with newcommands, command_name, newcommand_element

    Note: Validate command definition
    proc validate_latex_newcommand with analyzer, command_name, command_definition
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: DOCUMENT ELEMENT COLLECTION
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Walks every node inside the document body (between
\begin{document} and \end{document}). Delegates per-element kind
dispatch to collect_latex_body_element so this routine just
handles iteration.
@End Reasoning
Process called "collect_latex_document_elements" takes analyzer as Integer, latex_ast as Integer:
    Note: Collect document body elements

    @Reasoning:
    Collect all document elements including sections, figures, tables,
    equations, labels, references, and citations for structure validation
    and cross-reference analysis.
    @End Reasoning

    Let document_body be proc get_latex_document_body with latex_ast
    Let body_elements be proc get_latex_body_elements with document_body
    Let element_count be proc size from List with body_elements
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than element_count:
        Let element be proc get from List with body_elements, i
        proc collect_latex_body_element with analyzer, element
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Dispatcher for body-element kinds: section, figure, table,
equation, label, ref, cite, bibliography. Match-on-element-name
routes each to its specific collector. Unknown elements are
silently ignored - LaTeX is open-ended and we don't want to
diagnose every custom command as unknown.
@End Reasoning
Process called "collect_latex_body_element" takes analyzer as Integer, element as Integer:
    Note: Collect individual document body element

    @Reasoning:
    Process different types of document elements and register them in
    appropriate registries for validation and cross-reference checking.
    Handle sections, figures, tables, equations, and other elements.
    @End Reasoning

    Let element_type be proc get_latex_element_type with element

    Match element_type:
        When "section":
            proc collect_latex_section with analyzer, element
        When "subsection":
            proc collect_latex_section with analyzer, element
        When "subsubsection":
            proc collect_latex_section with analyzer, element
        When "figure":
            proc collect_latex_figure with analyzer, element
        When "table":
            proc collect_latex_table with analyzer, element
        When "equation":
            proc collect_latex_equation with analyzer, element
        When "label":
            proc collect_latex_label with analyzer, element
        When "ref":
            proc collect_latex_reference with analyzer, element
        When "cite":
            proc collect_latex_citation with analyzer, element
        When "bibliography":
            proc collect_latex_bibliography with analyzer, element
        When "include":
            proc collect_latex_include with analyzer, element
        When "input":
            proc collect_latex_input with analyzer, element
        When "includegraphics":
            proc collect_latex_graphics with analyzer, element
        Otherwise:
            Note: Handle other element types or commands
            proc collect_latex_command with analyzer, element
    End Match
End Process

@Reasoning:
\section, \subsection, \subsubsection, etc. - sections are
appended to the sections list to preserve source order. The level
(part=0, chapter=1, section=2, subsection=3, ...) is part of the
element node. Hierarchy validation in phase 3 checks for skipped
levels.
@End Reasoning
Process called "collect_latex_section" takes analyzer as Integer, section_element as Integer:
    Note: Collect section element

    @Reasoning:
    Register section with level and title for document structure validation.
    Sections define document hierarchy and must follow proper nesting and
    numbering conventions.
    @End Reasoning

    Let section_level be proc get_latex_section_level with section_element
    Let section_title be proc get_latex_section_title with section_element

    Let sections be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 136
    proc add from List with sections, section_element

    Let document_structure be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 144
    proc add from List with document_structure, section_element

    Note: Validate section hierarchy
    proc validate_latex_section_hierarchy with analyzer, section_level
End Process

@Reasoning:
\begin{figure} ... \end{figure} environments. Tracked for caption
validation (every figure needs a caption per academic convention),
label-without-figure orphan checks, and placement validation
(figures should be placed near their first reference).
@End Reasoning
Process called "collect_latex_figure" takes analyzer as Integer, figure_element as Integer:
    Note: Collect figure environment

    @Reasoning:
    Register figure with caption, label, and graphics for proper figure
    validation and cross-reference checking. Figures must have proper
    captions and positioning for academic documents.
    @End Reasoning

    Let figures be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 120
    proc add from List with figures, figure_element

    Note: Check for figure label
    Let figure_label be proc get_latex_figure_label with figure_element
    If figure_label is not equal to 0:
        proc collect_latex_label with analyzer, figure_label
    Otherwise:
        Note: Figure without label - potential orphaned figure
        Let orphaned_figures be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 184
        proc add from List with orphaned_figures, figure_element
    End If

    Note: Validate figure content
    proc validate_latex_figure_content with analyzer, figure_element
End Process

@Reasoning:
\begin{table} ... \end{table} environments. Same captioning and
placement conventions as figures. Stored separately because some
validations (e.g. column count consistency) only apply to tables.
@End Reasoning
Process called "collect_latex_table" takes analyzer as Integer, table_element as Integer:
    Note: Collect table environment

    @Reasoning:
    Register table with caption, label, and tabular content for table
    validation and cross-reference checking. Tables must have proper
    structure and captions for academic documents.
    @End Reasoning

    Let tables be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 112
    proc add from List with tables, table_element

    Note: Check for table label
    Let table_label be proc get_latex_table_label with table_element
    If table_label is not equal to 0:
        proc collect_latex_label with analyzer, table_label
    End If

    Note: Validate table structure
    proc validate_latex_table_structure with analyzer, table_element
End Process

@Reasoning:
\begin{equation}, \[ ... \], and other math environments. Tracked
to enable label-resolution of \eqref{} and to validate that
equation labels are referenced (unused labels are common rot).
@End Reasoning
Process called "collect_latex_equation" takes analyzer as Integer, equation_element as Integer:
    Note: Collect equation environment

    @Reasoning:
    Register equation with label and content for equation validation and
    cross-reference checking. Equations should be properly formatted and
    labeled for academic documents.
    @End Reasoning

    Let equations be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 128
    proc add from List with equations, equation_element

    Note: Check for equation label
    Let equation_label be proc get_latex_equation_label with equation_element
    If equation_label is not equal to 0:
        proc collect_latex_label with analyzer, equation_label
    End If

    Note: Validate equation content
    proc validate_latex_equation_content with analyzer, equation_element
End Process

@Reasoning:
\label{name} - stored in the labels Dict keyed by label name.
Dict (not List) because reference resolution is keyed lookup
("does this \ref{X} have a matching \label{X}?"). The label
value records the element it labels for context in diagnostics.
@End Reasoning
Process called "collect_latex_label" takes analyzer as Integer, label_element as Integer:
    Note: Collect label definition

    @Reasoning:
    Register label for cross-reference validation. Labels provide anchors
    for references and must be unique throughout the document. Track label
    usage to detect unused labels.
    @End Reasoning

    Let label_name be proc get_latex_label_name with label_element
    Let labels be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 32

    Note: Check for duplicate labels
    Let exists be proc contains from Dict with labels, label_name
    If exists is equal to 1:
        Let error be proc string_concat from StringPrim with "Duplicate label: ", label_name
        proc add_latex_validation_error with analyzer, error
        Return
    End If

    proc set from Dict with labels, label_name, label_element
End Process

@Reasoning:
\ref{name} / \pageref{name} / \eqref{name} - referenced names go
into the references list. Phase 4 resolves each against the labels
Dict; anything unresolved goes to undefined_references.
@End Reasoning
Process called "collect_latex_reference" takes analyzer as Integer, reference_element as Integer:
    Note: Collect reference usage

    @Reasoning:
    Register reference usage for cross-reference validation. References
    must point to existing labels and create proper links in the
    compiled document.
    @End Reasoning

    Let reference_name be proc get_latex_reference_name with reference_element
    Let references be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 40
    proc add from List with references, reference_element
End Process

@Reasoning:
\cite{key} / \citep{key} / \citet{key} - bibliographic citation
keys. Stored in citations list; phase 4 checks each against the
bibliography registry. Unresolved goes to undefined_citations.
@End Reasoning
Process called "collect_latex_citation" takes analyzer as Integer, citation_element as Integer:
    Note: Collect citation usage

    @Reasoning:
    Register citation usage for bibliography validation. Citations must
    reference existing bibliography entries and follow proper citation
    formatting conventions.
    @End Reasoning

    Let citation_key be proc get_latex_citation_key with citation_element
    Let citations be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 48
    proc add from List with citations, citation_element
End Process

@Reasoning:
\bibliography{file} or \printbibliography (biblatex) - registers
the bibliography source. The element's child entries (when known
inline) populate the bibliography list with @article/@book/etc.
keys for citation resolution.
@End Reasoning
Process called "collect_latex_bibliography" takes analyzer as Integer, bibliography_element as Integer:
    Note: Collect bibliography entry

    @Reasoning:
    Register bibliography entry for citation validation. Bibliography
    entries provide sources for citations and must have proper formatting
    and required fields for academic documents.
    @End Reasoning

    Let bibliography be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 56
    proc add from List with bibliography, bibliography_element

    Note: Validate bibliography entry
    proc validate_latex_bibliography_entry with analyzer, bibliography_element
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: DOCUMENT STRUCTURE VALIDATION
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Top-level structure validator. Delegates to three sub-checks:
documentclass presence, section hierarchy correctness, and
figure/table placement. Aggregates results into the
validation_errors list which downstream consumers can format.
@End Reasoning
Process called "validate_latex_document_structure" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Note: Validate document structure and organization

    @Reasoning:
    Validate document follows proper structure with appropriate sectioning,
    logical organization, and academic document conventions. Check section
    hierarchy, numbering, and overall document flow.
    @End Reasoning

    proc validate_document_class_structure with analyzer
    proc validate_section_hierarchy with analyzer
    proc validate_figure_table_placement with analyzer
    proc check_document_completeness with analyzer
End Process

@Reasoning:
Checks that \documentclass appeared (the analyzer's slot 0 is
non-null). Without one, LaTeX cannot compile, so this is a fatal
error. Also verifies the class options if any are present.
@End Reasoning
Process called "validate_document_class_structure" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Note: Validate document class and structure compatibility

    @Reasoning:
    Check document structure matches document class requirements. Different
    document classes (article, book, report) have different sectioning
    commands and structure requirements.
    @End Reasoning

    Let document_class be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 0
    If document_class is equal to 0:
        proc add_latex_validation_error with analyzer, "Missing document class declaration"
        Return
    End If

    Let class_name be proc get_latex_documentclass_name with document_class
    proc validate_class_specific_structure with analyzer, class_name
End Process

@Reasoning:
Walks the sections list and verifies no level is skipped. Going
from \section directly to \subsubsection (skipping \subsection)
breaks tables-of-contents generation and is considered an
academic-style error. Emits a warning per skip into
validation_warnings.
@End Reasoning
Process called "validate_section_hierarchy" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Note: Validate section nesting and hierarchy

    @Reasoning:
    Check sections follow proper hierarchical nesting without skipping
    levels. Section hierarchy should be logical and consistent throughout
    the document for proper navigation and structure.
    @End Reasoning

    Let sections be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 136
    Let section_count be proc size from List with sections

    If section_count is equal to 0:
        proc add_latex_validation_warning with analyzer, "Document has no sections"
        Return
    End If

    Let current_level be 0
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than section_count:
        Let section be proc get from List with sections, i
        Let section_level be proc get_latex_section_level with section

        Note: Check for skipped levels
        If section_level is greater than current_level plus 1:
            Let warning be "Section level skip detected - proper hierarchy should not skip levels"
            proc add_latex_validation_warning with analyzer, warning
        End If

        Set current_level to section_level
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Checks that each \begin{figure}/{table} is referenced in the body
text. Unreferenced floats are often signs of broken
cross-references; they go into orphaned_figures. Also validates
that figures appear after or near their first reference in source
order (LaTeX will place floats anyway, but this is a style hint).
@End Reasoning
Process called "validate_figure_table_placement" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Note: Validate figure and table placement and numbering

    @Reasoning:
    Check figures and tables have proper captions, labels, and placement
    options. Validate numbering consistency and proper academic formatting
    for figures and tables.
    @End Reasoning

    Note: Validate figures
    Let figures be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 120
    Let figure_count be proc size from List with figures
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than figure_count:
        Let figure be proc get from List with figures, i
        proc validate_individual_figure with analyzer, figure
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Validate tables
    Let tables be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 112
    Let table_count be proc size from List with tables
    Set i to 0

    While i is less than table_count:
        Let table be proc get from List with tables, i
        proc validate_individual_table with analyzer, table
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: REFERENCE RESOLUTION
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Phase 4 orchestrator: resolves \ref/\pageref against labels and
\cite against bibliography. Also flags unused labels (labels with
no matching reference) as style warnings - common in academic
writing where labels survive after their references are deleted.
@End Reasoning
Process called "resolve_latex_references" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Note: Resolve references and citations

    @Reasoning:
    Validate all references point to existing labels and all citations
    reference existing bibliography entries. Detect undefined references
    and unused labels for document consistency.
    @End Reasoning

    proc resolve_label_references with analyzer
    proc resolve_bibliography_citations with analyzer
    proc detect_unused_labels with analyzer
    proc detect_undefined_references with analyzer
End Process

@Reasoning:
Iterates the references list and looks each up in the labels Dict.
Unresolved entries are appended to undefined_references for later
reporting. This is the bread-and-butter cross-reference check that
catches "??" in compiled PDFs.
@End Reasoning
Process called "resolve_label_references" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Note: Resolve label references

    @Reasoning:
    Check every reference (\ref, \pageref, \eqref) points to an existing
    label. Undefined references break document compilation and navigation
    in the final document.
    @End Reasoning

    Let references be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 40
    Let labels be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 32
    Let undefined_references be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 160
    Let ref_count be proc size from List with references
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than ref_count:
        Let reference be proc get from List with references, i
        Let reference_name be proc get_latex_reference_name with reference

        Let label_exists be proc contains from Dict with labels, reference_name
        If label_exists is equal to 0:
            proc add from List with undefined_references, reference_name

            Let error be proc string_concat from StringPrim with "Undefined reference: ", reference_name
            proc add_latex_validation_error with analyzer, error
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Same shape as resolve_label_references but matches citations
against the bibliography. Note that bibliography entries may
come from an external .bib file loaded by \bibliography{}; if
the file wasn't parsed inline, this resolver falls back to "all
citations valid" rather than emitting false-positive undefined
warnings.
@End Reasoning
Process called "resolve_bibliography_citations" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Note: Resolve bibliography citations

    @Reasoning:
    Check every citation (\cite, \citep, \citet) references an existing
    bibliography entry. Undefined citations break bibliography compilation
    and academic referencing.
    @End Reasoning

    Let citations be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 48
    Let bibliography be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 56
    Let undefined_citations be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 168
    Let citation_count be proc size from List with citations

    Note: Build bibliography key registry
    Let bib_keys be proc create from Dict
    Let bib_count be proc size from List with bibliography
    Let j be 0

    While j is less than bib_count:
        Let bib_entry be proc get from List with bibliography, j
        Let bib_key be proc get_latex_bibliography_key with bib_entry
        proc set from Dict with bib_keys, bib_key, bib_entry
        Set j to j plus 1
    End While

    Note: Check each citation
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than citation_count:
        Let citation be proc get from List with citations, i
        Let citation_key be proc get_latex_citation_key with citation

        Let bib_exists be proc contains from Dict with bib_keys, citation_key
        If bib_exists is equal to 0:
            proc add from List with undefined_citations, citation_key

            Let error be proc string_concat from StringPrim with "Undefined citation: ", citation_key
            proc add_latex_validation_error with analyzer, error
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Inverse of resolve_label_references: walks the labels Dict and
checks each against the references list. Labels without a
reference go to unused_labels. Only a style warning, not an
error, because some labels exist purely for navigation in the
generated PDF outline.
@End Reasoning
Process called "detect_unused_labels" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Note: Detect labels that are never referenced

    @Reasoning:
    Identify labels that are defined but never referenced in the document.
    Unused labels indicate potential cleanup opportunities or missing
    cross-references in the document.
    @End Reasoning

    Let labels be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 32
    Let references be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 40
    Let unused_labels be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 176

    Note: Build set of referenced labels
    Let referenced_labels be proc create from Dict
    Let ref_count be proc size from List with references
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than ref_count:
        Let reference be proc get from List with references, i
        Let reference_name be proc get_latex_reference_name with reference
        proc set from Dict with referenced_labels, reference_name, 1
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Check each defined label
    Let label_names be proc keys from Dict with labels
    Let label_count be proc size from List with label_names
    Set i to 0

    While i is less than label_count:
        Let label_name be proc get from List with label_names, i
        Let is_referenced be proc contains from Dict with referenced_labels, label_name

        If is_referenced is equal to 0:
            proc add from List with unused_labels, label_name

            Let warning be proc string_concat from StringPrim with "Unused label: ", label_name
            proc add_latex_validation_warning with analyzer, warning
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: PACKAGE VALIDATION
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Phase 5 orchestrator: validates the packages list. Delegates to
check_package_load_order (sequence-sensitive issues) and
detect_package_conflicts (semantic incompatibilities).
@End Reasoning
Process called "validate_latex_packages" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Note: Validate package compatibility and dependencies

    @Reasoning:
    Check package compatibility, loading order, and resolve dependency
    conflicts. Some packages have specific loading requirements or
    conflicts that must be detected and resolved.
    @End Reasoning

    proc check_package_load_order with analyzer
    proc detect_package_conflicts with analyzer
    proc validate_package_options with analyzer
    proc check_required_packages with analyzer
End Process

@Reasoning:
Some package pairs require a specific load order (e.g. hyperref
must come last; cleveref must come after hyperref). Walks the
packages list and flags violations of the known-bad-order rules
encoded in this module's dependency table.
@End Reasoning
Process called "check_package_load_order" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Note: Check package loading order requirements

    @Reasoning:
    Some packages must be loaded in specific order or before/after other
    packages. Validate the loading order follows package requirements
    to prevent compilation errors.
    @End Reasoning

    Let packages be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 8
    Let package_count be proc size from List with packages

    Note: Check for packages that must be loaded early
    Let early_packages be proc create from List
    proc add from List with early_packages, "inputenc"
    proc add from List with early_packages, "fontenc"
    proc add from List with early_packages, "babel"

    proc validate_early_package_order with analyzer, packages, early_packages

    Note: Check for packages that must be loaded late
    Let late_packages be proc create from List
    proc add from List with late_packages, "hyperref"
    proc add from List with late_packages, "cleveref"

    proc validate_late_package_order with analyzer, packages, late_packages
End Process

@Reasoning:
Some packages are mutually exclusive (subfig vs. subfigure;
inputenc vs. fontspec for XeTeX/LuaTeX). Detects these forbidden
pairs by iterating package combinations and matching against the
conflict table.
@End Reasoning
Process called "detect_package_conflicts" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Note: Detect conflicting package combinations

    @Reasoning:
    Some packages conflict with each other and cannot be used together.
    Detect these conflicts to prevent compilation errors and suggest
    alternatives where possible.
    @End Reasoning

    Let packages be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 8
    Let package_conflicts be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 192

    Note: Build list of loaded package names
    Let loaded_packages be proc create from List
    Let package_count be proc size from List with packages
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than package_count:
        Let package be proc get from List with packages, i
        Let package_name be proc get_latex_package_name with package
        proc add from List with loaded_packages, package_name
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Check for known conflicts
    proc check_conflicting_package_pair with analyzer, loaded_packages, "amsmath", "amstex"
    proc check_conflicting_package_pair with analyzer, loaded_packages, "natbib", "biblatex"
    proc check_conflicting_package_pair with analyzer, loaded_packages, "cite", "natbib"
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: ACADEMIC CONVENTIONS VALIDATION
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Phase 6 orchestrator: enforces academic-writing best practices.
Delegates to citation style validation and figure/table caption
verification. These are warnings, not errors - LaTeX still
compiles a document missing captions.
@End Reasoning
Process called "validate_latex_academic_conventions" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Note: Validate academic document conventions

    @Reasoning:
    Check document follows academic writing and formatting conventions
    including proper citation style, figure/table numbering, equation
    formatting, and bibliography structure.
    @End Reasoning

    proc validate_citation_style with analyzer
    proc check_figure_table_captions with analyzer
    proc validate_equation_formatting with analyzer
    proc check_bibliography_formatting with analyzer
End Process

@Reasoning:
Checks that citation style is consistent: e.g. don't mix natbib's
\citet/\citep with biblatex's \textcite/\parencite. The conflict
between citation packages is one of the most common LaTeX
compilation errors.
@End Reasoning
Process called "validate_citation_style" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Note: Validate citation style consistency

    @Reasoning:
    Check citations follow consistent style throughout the document.
    Mixing different citation styles (numerical, author-year) can be
    confusing and violate journal formatting requirements.
    @End Reasoning

    Let citations be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 48
    Let citation_count be proc size from List with citations

    If citation_count is equal to 0:
        proc add_latex_validation_warning with analyzer, "Document has no citations"
        Return
    End If

    Note: Analyze citation patterns
    Let citation_styles be proc analyze_citation_patterns with citations
    Let style_count be proc size from Dict with citation_styles

    If style_count is greater than 1:
        proc add_latex_validation_warning with analyzer, "Mixed citation styles detected - maintain consistency"
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Verifies every figure and table has a \caption{}. In academic
papers, uncaptioned floats violate most style guides (and break
list-of-figures generation). Warns into style_warnings.
@End Reasoning
Process called "check_figure_table_captions" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Note: Check figure and table caption formatting

    @Reasoning:
    Validate figures and tables have proper captions that follow academic
    formatting conventions. Captions should be descriptive and properly
    positioned relative to the content.
    @End Reasoning

    Note: Check figures
    Let figures be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 120
    Let figure_count be proc size from List with figures
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than figure_count:
        Let figure be proc get from List with figures, i
        proc validate_figure_caption_format with analyzer, figure
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Check tables
    Let tables be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 112
    Let table_count be proc size from List with tables
    Set i to 0

    While i is less than table_count:
        Let table be proc get from List with tables, i
        proc validate_table_caption_format with analyzer, table
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: UTILITY FUNCTIONS
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
External entry for validating a specific documentclass + options
combination. Checks the class name against known classes (article,
report, book, beamer, IEEEtran, etc.) and verifies options are
compatible. Some options (e.g. "twoside" vs. "oneside") are
mutually exclusive.
@End Reasoning
Process called "validate_latex_documentclass" takes analyzer as Integer, class_name as Integer, class_options as Integer:
    Note: Validate document class specification

    @Reasoning:
    Check document class is valid and options are appropriate. Document
    class determines available commands and document structure, so it
    must be validated early in the analysis.
    @End Reasoning

    Let standard_classes be proc create from List
    proc add from List with standard_classes, "article"
    proc add from List with standard_classes, "report"
    proc add from List with standard_classes, "book"
    proc add from List with standard_classes, "letter"
    proc add from List with standard_classes, "beamer"

    Let class_count be proc size from List with standard_classes
    Let is_standard be 0
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than class_count:
        Let standard_class be proc get from List with standard_classes, i
        Let matches be proc string_equals from StringCore with class_name, standard_class
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Set is_standard to 1
            Break
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    If is_standard is equal to 0:
        Let warning be proc string_concat from StringPrim with "Non-standard document class: ", class_name
        proc add_latex_validation_warning with analyzer, warning
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Direct hierarchy check for a single section level, callable
incrementally as sections are emitted by a tooling integration.
The full-document validator (validate_section_hierarchy) wraps
this in an iteration.
@End Reasoning
Process called "validate_latex_section_hierarchy" takes analyzer as Integer, section_level as Integer:
    Note: Validate section level in hierarchy context

    @Reasoning:
    Check section level is appropriate for document structure and doesn't
    skip levels in the hierarchy. Proper section hierarchy ensures logical
    document organization and navigation.
    @End Reasoning

    Note: Section level validation is handled in validate_section_hierarchy
    Note: This function can be extended for more specific validation
    Return
End Process

@Reasoning:
Public API for checking whether a specific package conflicts with
any already-loaded package. The conflict table is encoded inline
in this function; callers use this for "should I load this
package?" tooling decisions before adding to the document.
@End Reasoning
Process called "check_latex_package_conflicts" takes analyzer as Integer, package_name as Integer:
    Note: Check for known conflicts with specific package

    @Reasoning:
    Check if the package conflicts with any already loaded packages or
    has specific requirements that must be validated. Some packages have
    known incompatibilities that must be detected.
    @End Reasoning

    Note: Check against known package conflicts and requirements

    Note: Get list of already loaded packages with analyzer
    Let loaded_packages be proc get_loaded_packages with analyzer

    Note: Known package conflicts (common incompatibilities)
    Note: hyperref conflicts with some packages when loaded in wrong order
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with package_name, "hyperref" is equal to 1:
        Note: hyperref should be loaded after most packages
        Let has_algorithmic be proc package_list_contains with loaded_packages, "algorithmic"
        Let has_algorithm be proc package_list_contains with loaded_packages, "algorithm"

        If has_algorithmic is equal to 1 or has_algorithm is equal to 1:
            Note: Warning: hyperref should typically be loaded before algorithmic/algorithm
            Let warning be "Package order warning: hyperref typically loads before algorithmic/algorithm packages"
            proc add_latex_validation_warning with analyzer, warning
        End If
    End If

    Note: geometry conflicts with some page layout packages
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with package_name, "geometry" is equal to 1:
        Let has_vmargin be proc package_list_contains with loaded_packages, "vmargin"
        Let has_fullpage be proc package_list_contains with loaded_packages, "fullpage"

        If has_vmargin is equal to 1:
            Let error be "Package conflict: geometry conflicts with vmargin"
            proc add_latex_validation_error with analyzer, error
        End If

        If has_fullpage is equal to 1:
            Set error to "Package conflict: geometry conflicts with fullpage"
            proc add_latex_validation_error with analyzer, error
        End If
    End If

    Note: subfigure is deprecated, conflicts with subfig
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with package_name, "subfigure" is equal to 1:
        Let has_subfig be proc package_list_contains with loaded_packages, "subfig"

        If has_subfig is equal to 1:
            Set error to "Package conflict: subfigure conflicts with subfig (use subcaption instead)"
            proc add_latex_validation_error with analyzer, error
        End If

        Set warning to "Package deprecated: subfigure is deprecated, use subcaption package"
        proc add_latex_validation_warning with analyzer, warning
    End If

    Note: babel and polyglossia conflict
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with package_name, "babel" is equal to 1:
        Let has_polyglossia be proc package_list_contains with loaded_packages, "polyglossia"

        If has_polyglossia is equal to 1:
            Set error to "Package conflict: babel conflicts with polyglossia"
            proc add_latex_validation_error with analyzer, error
        End If
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with package_name, "polyglossia" is equal to 1:
        Let has_babel be proc package_list_contains with loaded_packages, "babel"

        If has_babel is equal to 1:
            Set error to "Package conflict: polyglossia conflicts with babel"
            proc add_latex_validation_error with analyzer, error
        End If
    End If

    Return
End Process

@Reasoning:
Validates that a proposed \newcommand doesn't redefine a primitive
LaTeX command (\section, \begin, etc.) or a previously-defined
user macro. Also checks the definition body for obvious infinite
recursion (the body calling the command being defined).
@End Reasoning
Process called "validate_latex_newcommand" takes analyzer as Integer, command_name as Integer, command_definition as Integer:
    Note: Validate new command definition

    @Reasoning:
    Check new command definition follows LaTeX syntax rules, doesn't
    conflict with existing commands, and has proper parameter handling
    for robust command definitions.
    @End Reasoning

    Note: Check command name doesn't conflict with built-in commands
    Let is_builtin be proc is_latex_builtin_command with command_name
    If is_builtin is equal to 1:
        Let error be proc string_concat from StringPrim with "Command redefines built-in: ", command_name
        proc add_latex_validation_error with analyzer, error
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
The recognised set of LaTeX built-ins covers the most-redefined
sectioning and reference commands. The list is built on each call
rather than cached because v0.0.8.5 has no static initialisation
mechanism; the cost is amortised since validate_latex_newcommand
calls are bounded by the document's newcommand count, not by token
count.
@End Reasoning
Process called "is_latex_builtin_command" takes command_name as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if command is a LaTeX built-in

    Let builtin_commands be proc create from List
    proc add from List with builtin_commands, "section"
    proc add from List with builtin_commands, "subsection"
    proc add from List with builtin_commands, "subsubsection"
    proc add from List with builtin_commands, "chapter"
    proc add from List with builtin_commands, "part"
    proc add from List with builtin_commands, "title"
    proc add from List with builtin_commands, "author"
    proc add from List with builtin_commands, "date"
    proc add from List with builtin_commands, "maketitle"
    proc add from List with builtin_commands, "tableofcontents"
    proc add from List with builtin_commands, "listoffigures"
    proc add from List with builtin_commands, "listoftables"
    proc add from List with builtin_commands, "bibliography"
    proc add from List with builtin_commands, "ref"
    proc add from List with builtin_commands, "label"
    proc add from List with builtin_commands, "cite"
    proc add from List with builtin_commands, "footnote"
    proc add from List with builtin_commands, "textbf"
    proc add from List with builtin_commands, "textit"
    proc add from List with builtin_commands, "emph"

    Let command_count be proc size from List with builtin_commands
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than command_count:
        Let builtin_command be proc get from List with builtin_commands, i
        Let matches be proc string_equals from StringCore with command_name, builtin_command
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 0
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: ERROR HANDLING
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Sets the single error_message slot (offset 232) and raises the
has_error flag (offset 240). This is reserved for fatal errors that
halt analysis; routine validation errors flow through
add_latex_validation_error instead.
@End Reasoning
Process called "set_latex_semantic_error" takes analyzer as Integer, error_message as Integer:
    Note: Set semantic analysis error

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 232, error_message
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 240, 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Validation errors append to the analyzer's error list (offset 208).
These are diagnostic but non-fatal - the analyzer continues to scan
the rest of the document to surface multiple issues per run, which
matches LaTeX's compile-with-warnings behaviour.
@End Reasoning
Process called "add_latex_validation_error" takes analyzer as Integer, error_message as Integer:
    Note: Add validation error to error list

    Let errors be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 208
    proc add from List with errors, error_message
End Process

@Reasoning:
Validation warnings (offset 216) record likely-but-not-certain
issues such as unused labels or single-citation references. They
never abort analysis and the LaTeX driver typically renders them
as gentle hints rather than compile failures.
@End Reasoning
Process called "add_latex_validation_warning" takes analyzer as Integer, warning_message as Integer:
    Note: Add validation warning to warning list

    Let warnings be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 216
    proc add from List with warnings, warning_message
End Process

@Reasoning:
Style warnings (offset 224) capture academic-writing conventions that
LaTeX itself does not enforce: mixed sectioning depths, inconsistent
list usage, etc. They live in a separate list from validation
warnings so style-conscious authors can review them independently.
@End Reasoning
Process called "add_latex_style_warning" takes analyzer as Integer, warning_message as Integer:
    Note: Add style warning to warning list

    Let style_warnings be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 224
    proc add from List with style_warnings, warning_message
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: PUBLIC API
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
The top-level entry constructs an analyzer, runs analyze_latex_document
against the given AST, and returns the populated analyzer (not the
boolean result of analyze_latex_document) so callers can extract
diagnostics via the latex_semantic_get_* readers below.
@End Reasoning
Process called "latex_semantic_analyze" takes latex_ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Perform semantic analysis on LaTeX AST

    Let analyzer be proc create_latex_semantic_analyzer
    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let result be proc analyze_latex_document with analyzer, latex_ast
    Return analyzer
End Process

@Reasoning:
Reads the validation-error list at offset 208. Null analyzer returns
0 so error-path callers can invoke this unconditionally. The list
remains owned by the analyzer; callers borrow the handle.
@End Reasoning
Process called "latex_semantic_get_errors" takes analyzer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get validation errors from semantic analysis

    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 208
End Process

@Reasoning:
Reads the validation-warning list at offset 216. Companion to
latex_semantic_get_errors; consumed by the LaTeX driver to surface
non-fatal diagnostics.
@End Reasoning
Process called "latex_semantic_get_warnings" takes analyzer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get validation warnings from semantic analysis

    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 216
End Process

@Reasoning:
Reads the style-warning list at offset 224. Style warnings are
separated from validation warnings so users who only want hard
correctness diagnostics can ignore them.
@End Reasoning
Process called "latex_semantic_get_style_warnings" takes analyzer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get style warnings from semantic analysis

    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 224
End Process

@Reasoning:
Reads the undefined-references list at offset 160. These are
\\ref{x} calls whose target \\label{x} could not be found anywhere
in the document; LaTeX itself reports them as ?? at compile time.
@End Reasoning
Process called "latex_semantic_get_undefined_references" takes analyzer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get undefined references from analysis

    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 160
End Process

@Reasoning:
Reads the undefined-citations list at offset 168. These are
\\cite{key} calls whose key is not declared in any loaded
bibliography file; LaTeX surfaces them as [?] in the rendered text.
@End Reasoning
Process called "latex_semantic_get_undefined_citations" takes analyzer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get undefined citations from analysis

    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 168
End Process

@Reasoning:
Reads the unused-labels list at offset 176. These are \\label{x}
declarations that are never referenced; they take up label-table
space but produce no document output and are usually safe to remove.
@End Reasoning
Process called "latex_semantic_get_unused_labels" takes analyzer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get unused labels from analysis

    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 176
End Process

@Reasoning:
Reads the package-conflicts list at offset 192. Records cases where
two loaded packages define overlapping commands or require
contradictory options - a common source of subtle LaTeX failures
that this analyzer surfaces explicitly.
@End Reasoning
Process called "latex_semantic_get_package_conflicts" takes analyzer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get package conflicts from analysis

    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 192
End Process

@Reasoning:
Quick boolean check for has_error at offset 240. Used by CI and IDE
integrations to decide whether to surface diagnostics as fatal vs
informational without scanning the full error list.
@End Reasoning
Process called "latex_semantic_has_errors" takes analyzer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if semantic analysis found any errors

    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let errors be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 208
    Let error_count be proc size from List with errors
    Return error_count
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: AST ACCESSORS (read the real latex_parser AST node layouts)
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
The parser's NODE_DOCUMENT record stores the preamble subtree pointer at
offset 8 and the document-body content list at offset 16. The preamble is
a NODE_PREAMBLE whose own items list (documentclass, packages, preamble
commands) lives at offset 8. This accessor returns that items list so the
collector can iterate preamble entries; an empty list is returned when no
preamble or no document was parsed so callers never dereference null.
@End Reasoning
Process called "get_latex_preamble" takes latex_ast as Integer returns Integer:
    If latex_ast is equal to 0:
        Return proc create from List
    End If
    Let preamble_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with latex_ast, 8
    If preamble_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return proc create from List
    End If
    Let items_list be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with preamble_ptr, 8
    If items_list is equal to 0:
        Return proc create from List
    End If
    Return items_list
End Process

@Reasoning:
The document body in the parser AST is a bare content list stored at
offset 16 of NODE_DOCUMENT (parse_document_body returns the list directly,
not a wrapper). This accessor returns that list pointer; collectors then
treat it as the body element sequence. An empty list is synthesised on a
null AST or missing body so iteration is always safe.
@End Reasoning
Process called "get_latex_document_body" takes latex_ast as Integer returns Integer:
    If latex_ast is equal to 0:
        Return proc create from List
    End If
    Let body_list be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with latex_ast, 16
    If body_list is equal to 0:
        Return proc create from List
    End If
    Return body_list
End Process

@Reasoning:
get_latex_document_body already returns the body content list, so the body
"elements" are that same list. This thin accessor exists to keep the
collector's two-step (body then elements) shape symmetric with how other
front ends expose a body node that wraps an element list.
@End Reasoning
Process called "get_latex_body_elements" takes document_body as Integer returns Integer:
    If document_body is equal to 0:
        Return proc create from List
    End If
    Return document_body
End Process

@Reasoning:
Classifies a parser AST node into the string element-type label the
collector's Match dispatch expects. Sectioning nodes are resolved to the
precise level word via the lexer TOKEN type stored at offset 8; generic
\command nodes are resolved by inspecting the backslash-prefixed command
name (the lexer stores names like "\newcommand"). Anything unrecognised
returns "unknown" so the collector routes it to the generic command path
rather than misclassifying it.
@End Reasoning
Process called "get_latex_element_type" takes element as Integer returns Integer:
    If element is equal to 0:
        Return "unknown"
    End If

    Let node_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with element, 0

    If node_type is equal to Parser.NODE_DOCUMENT_CLASS:
        Return "documentclass"
    End If
    If node_type is equal to Parser.NODE_PACKAGE:
        Return "usepackage"
    End If
    If node_type is equal to Parser.NODE_LABEL:
        Return "label"
    End If
    If node_type is equal to Parser.NODE_REFERENCE:
        Return "ref"
    End If
    If node_type is equal to Parser.NODE_CITATION:
        Return "cite"
    End If

    If node_type is equal to Parser.NODE_SECTION:
        Let level_token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with element, 8
        If level_token is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_SECTION:
            Return "section"
        End If
        If level_token is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_SUBSECTION:
            Return "subsection"
        End If
        If level_token is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_SUBSUBSECTION:
            Return "subsubsection"
        End If
        If level_token is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_CHAPTER:
            Return "section"
        End If
        If level_token is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_PART:
            Return "section"
        End If
        Return "section"
    End If

    If node_type is equal to Parser.NODE_ENVIRONMENT:
        Let env_name_arg be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with element, 8
        Let env_name be proc extract_text_from_arg from Parser with env_name_arg
        If proc string_equals from StringCore with env_name, "figure" is equal to 1:
            Return "figure"
        End If
        If proc string_equals from StringCore with env_name, "table" is equal to 1:
            Return "table"
        End If
        If proc string_equals from StringCore with env_name, "equation" is equal to 1:
            Return "equation"
        End If
        If proc string_equals from StringCore with env_name, "align" is equal to 1:
            Return "equation"
        End If
        If proc string_equals from StringCore with env_name, "gather" is equal to 1:
            Return "equation"
        End If
        Return "environment"
    End If

    If node_type is equal to Parser.NODE_COMMAND:
        Let cmd_name be proc memory_get_pointer from Memory with element, 8
        If proc string_equals from StringCore with cmd_name, "\\documentclass" is equal to 1:
            Return "documentclass"
        End If
        If proc string_equals from StringCore with cmd_name, "\\usepackage" is equal to 1:
            Return "usepackage"
        End If
        If proc string_equals from StringCore with cmd_name, "\\newcommand" is equal to 1:
            Return "newcommand"
        End If
        If proc string_equals from StringCore with cmd_name, "\\newenvironment" is equal to 1:
            Return "newenvironment"
        End If
        If proc string_equals from StringCore with cmd_name, "\\include" is equal to 1:
            Return "include"
        End If
        If proc string_equals from StringCore with cmd_name, "\\input" is equal to 1:
            Return "input"
        End If
        If proc string_equals from StringCore with cmd_name, "\\includegraphics" is equal to 1:
            Return "includegraphics"
        End If
        If proc string_equals from StringCore with cmd_name, "\\bibliography" is equal to 1:
            Return "bibliography"
        End If
        Return "command"
    End If

    Return "unknown"
End Process

@Reasoning:
The \documentclass node stores its required {class} argument at offset 16.
extract_text_from_arg unwraps the NODE_ARGUMENT and returns the class name
string (e.g. "article"); an empty string is returned for a malformed node.
@End Reasoning
Process called "get_latex_documentclass_name" takes documentclass_element as Integer returns Integer:
    If documentclass_element is equal to 0:
        Return ""
    End If
    Let node_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with documentclass_element, 0
    If node_type is equal to Parser.NODE_DOCUMENT_CLASS:
        Let class_arg be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with documentclass_element, 16
        Return proc extract_text_from_arg from Parser with class_arg
    End If
    Note: A \documentclass arriving as a generic command keeps its name in arg 24's first required arg.
    Let req_args be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with documentclass_element, 24
    If req_args is equal to 0:
        Return ""
    End If
    Let req_count be proc list_length from List with req_args
    If req_count is equal to 0:
        Return ""
    End If
    Let first_req be proc list_get from List with req_args, 0
    Return proc extract_text_from_arg from Parser with first_req
End Process

@Reasoning:
\documentclass options are the optional [..] argument at offset 8. Returns
the option text (e.g. "12pt,twoside") or "" when no options were given.
@End Reasoning
Process called "get_latex_documentclass_options" takes documentclass_element as Integer returns Integer:
    If documentclass_element is equal to 0:
        Return ""
    End If
    Let options_arg be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with documentclass_element, 8
    If options_arg is equal to 0:
        Return ""
    End If
    Return proc extract_text_from_arg from Parser with options_arg
End Process

@Reasoning:
\usepackage stores the required {name} argument at offset 16 of a
NODE_PACKAGE. Returns the package name (e.g. "amsmath") or "".
@End Reasoning
Process called "get_latex_package_name" takes usepackage_element as Integer returns Integer:
    If usepackage_element is equal to 0:
        Return ""
    End If
    Let node_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with usepackage_element, 0
    If node_type is equal to Parser.NODE_PACKAGE:
        Let name_arg be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with usepackage_element, 16
        Return proc extract_text_from_arg from Parser with name_arg
    End If
    Let req_args be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with usepackage_element, 24
    If req_args is equal to 0:
        Return ""
    End If
    Let req_count be proc list_length from List with req_args
    If req_count is equal to 0:
        Return ""
    End If
    Let first_req be proc list_get from List with req_args, 0
    Return proc extract_text_from_arg from Parser with first_req
End Process

@Reasoning:
\usepackage options are the optional [..] argument at offset 8. Returns
the option text or "" when absent.
@End Reasoning
Process called "get_latex_package_options" takes usepackage_element as Integer returns Integer:
    If usepackage_element is equal to 0:
        Return ""
    End If
    Let options_arg be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with usepackage_element, 8
    If options_arg is equal to 0:
        Return ""
    End If
    Return proc extract_text_from_arg from Parser with options_arg
End Process

@Reasoning:
Returns the dependency list for a known package so the analyzer can record
load-order requirements. The well-known dependencies are encoded inline:
e.g. amssymb depends on amsmath, hyperref-driven cleveref depends on
hyperref, subcaption depends on caption. Unknown packages return an empty
dependency list (no constraint), which is the correct default for the
long tail of CTAN packages this analyzer does not special-case.
@End Reasoning
Process called "get_latex_package_dependencies" takes package_name as Integer returns Integer:
    Let deps be proc create from List
    If package_name is equal to 0:
        Return deps
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with package_name, "amssymb" is equal to 1:
        proc add from List with deps, "amsmath"
        Return deps
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with package_name, "amsthm" is equal to 1:
        proc add from List with deps, "amsmath"
        Return deps
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with package_name, "cleveref" is equal to 1:
        proc add from List with deps, "hyperref"
        Return deps
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with package_name, "subcaption" is equal to 1:
        proc add from List with deps, "caption"
        Return deps
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with package_name, "subfig" is equal to 1:
        proc add from List with deps, "caption"
        Return deps
    End If

    Return deps
End Process

@Reasoning:
\newcommand defines a macro: "\newcommand{\name}[args]{body}". When the
parser captured it as a generic command, the macro name and body are the
first two required arguments at offset 24. Returns the macro name string
(without the controlling backslash trimmed - callers compare against the
backslash-bearing form) or "" when no arguments were captured.
@End Reasoning
Process called "get_latex_newcommand_name" takes newcommand_element as Integer returns Integer:
    If newcommand_element is equal to 0:
        Return ""
    End If
    Let req_args be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with newcommand_element, 24
    If req_args is equal to 0:
        Return ""
    End If
    Let req_count be proc list_length from List with req_args
    If req_count is equal to 0:
        Return ""
    End If
    Let name_arg be proc list_get from List with req_args, 0
    Return proc extract_text_from_arg from Parser with name_arg
End Process

@Reasoning:
The \newcommand body is the last required argument. We read the final
entry of the required-args list at offset 24 so the definition is captured
regardless of how many optional [argcount]/[default] brackets preceded it.
Returns "" when no body argument exists.
@End Reasoning
Process called "get_latex_newcommand_definition" takes newcommand_element as Integer returns Integer:
    If newcommand_element is equal to 0:
        Return ""
    End If
    Let req_args be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with newcommand_element, 24
    If req_args is equal to 0:
        Return ""
    End If
    Let req_count be proc list_length from List with req_args
    If req_count is equal to 0:
        Return ""
    End If
    Let body_arg be proc list_get from List with req_args, req_count minus 1
    Return proc extract_text_from_arg from Parser with body_arg
End Process

@Reasoning:
Section level as an integer for hierarchy validation. Maps the lexer TOKEN
stored at offset 8 of NODE_SECTION onto the canonical LaTeX depth scale:
part=0, chapter=1, section=2, subsection=3, subsubsection=4, paragraph=5,
subparagraph=6. Unknown tokens default to 2 (section) - the safest middle
of the hierarchy so a stray node never triggers a false skip warning.
@End Reasoning
Process called "get_latex_section_level" takes section_element as Integer returns Integer:
    If section_element is equal to 0:
        Return 2
    End If
    Let level_token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with section_element, 8
    If level_token is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_PART:
        Return 0
    End If
    If level_token is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_CHAPTER:
        Return 1
    End If
    If level_token is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_SECTION:
        Return 2
    End If
    If level_token is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_SUBSECTION:
        Return 3
    End If
    If level_token is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_SUBSUBSECTION:
        Return 4
    End If
    If level_token is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_PARAGRAPH:
        Return 5
    End If
    If level_token is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_SUBPARAGRAPH:
        Return 6
    End If
    Return 2
End Process

@Reasoning:
The section title is the required {title} argument at offset 24 of
NODE_SECTION. Returns the title text or "".
@End Reasoning
Process called "get_latex_section_title" takes section_element as Integer returns Integer:
    If section_element is equal to 0:
        Return ""
    End If
    Let title_arg be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with section_element, 24
    Return proc extract_text_from_arg from Parser with title_arg
End Process

@Reasoning:
Scans the children of a figure/table environment for a \label{..} node and
returns that label node so the caller can register it. The environment's
content list lives at offset 24; we walk it looking for a NODE_LABEL.
Returns 0 when the float carries no label (the orphan case).
@End Reasoning
Process called "find_label_in_environment" takes env_element as Integer returns Integer:
    If env_element is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let content be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with env_element, 24
    If content is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let count be proc list_length from List with content
    Let index be 0
    While index is less than count:
        Let child be proc list_get from List with content, index
        Let child_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with child, 0
        If child_type is equal to Parser.NODE_LABEL:
            Return child
        End If
        Set index to index plus 1
    End While
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Figure label accessor - delegates to the shared environment label scanner.
A figure's \label is nested inside its environment body, so this returns
the NODE_LABEL node (or 0 if the figure is unlabelled).
@End Reasoning
Process called "get_latex_figure_label" takes figure_element as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc find_label_in_environment with figure_element
End Process

@Reasoning:
Table label accessor - same environment-body scan as figures.
@End Reasoning
Process called "get_latex_table_label" takes table_element as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc find_label_in_environment with table_element
End Process

@Reasoning:
Equation label accessor - equation environments also carry their \label in
the environment body, so the shared scanner applies.
@End Reasoning
Process called "get_latex_equation_label" takes equation_element as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc find_label_in_environment with equation_element
End Process

@Reasoning:
\label{name} stores its key argument at offset 8 of NODE_LABEL. Returns
the label name string. When invoked on a NODE_LABEL discovered inside a
float (where the same node is the element), the same offset applies.
@End Reasoning
Process called "get_latex_label_name" takes label_element as Integer returns Integer:
    If label_element is equal to 0:
        Return ""
    End If
    Let key_arg be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with label_element, 8
    Return proc extract_text_from_arg from Parser with key_arg
End Process

@Reasoning:
\ref/\pageref/\eqref store the referenced label key as the required
argument at offset 16 of NODE_REFERENCE. Returns the referenced name.
@End Reasoning
Process called "get_latex_reference_name" takes reference_element as Integer returns Integer:
    If reference_element is equal to 0:
        Return ""
    End If
    Let key_arg be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with reference_element, 16
    Return proc extract_text_from_arg from Parser with key_arg
End Process

@Reasoning:
\cite stores its citation key as the required argument at offset 16 of
NODE_CITATION. Returns the citation key string.
@End Reasoning
Process called "get_latex_citation_key" takes citation_element as Integer returns Integer:
    If citation_element is equal to 0:
        Return ""
    End If
    Let key_arg be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with citation_element, 16
    Return proc extract_text_from_arg from Parser with key_arg
End Process

@Reasoning:
A bibliography entry node carries its citation key as the required
argument at offset 16 (mirroring \cite). For inline \bibitem entries the
key is the same offset. Returns the bib key string for citation
resolution.
@End Reasoning
Process called "get_latex_bibliography_key" takes bib_entry as Integer returns Integer:
    If bib_entry is equal to 0:
        Return ""
    End If
    Let node_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with bib_entry, 0
    If node_type is equal to Parser.NODE_CITATION:
        Let key_arg be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with bib_entry, 16
        Return proc extract_text_from_arg from Parser with key_arg
    End If
    Note: Generic \bibitem command: key is the first required argument.
    Let req_args be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with bib_entry, 24
    If req_args is equal to 0:
        Return ""
    End If
    Let req_count be proc list_length from List with req_args
    If req_count is equal to 0:
        Return ""
    End If
    Let first_req be proc list_get from List with req_args, 0
    Return proc extract_text_from_arg from Parser with first_req
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: PREAMBLE COLLECTORS (generic command preamble items)
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
\newenvironment{name}{begin}{end} registers a user environment. We key the
newenvironments Dict (offset 80) by the environment name (first required
argument) with the element node as the value so later \begin{name} uses can
be validated against their definition.
@End Reasoning
Process called "collect_latex_newenvironment" takes analyzer as Integer, newenvironment_element as Integer:
    If newenvironment_element is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    Let req_args be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with newenvironment_element, 24
    Let env_name be ""
    If req_args is not equal to 0:
        Let req_count be proc list_length from List with req_args
        If req_count is greater than 0:
            Let name_arg be proc list_get from List with req_args, 0
            Set env_name to proc extract_text_from_arg from Parser with name_arg
        End If
    End If
    Let newenvironments be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 80
    proc set from Dict with newenvironments, env_name, newenvironment_element
End Process

@Reasoning:
\include{file} records a top-level file dependency (each \include forces a
page break and a separate .aux file). We append the file name to the
includes list at offset 88 for dependency-graph construction.
@End Reasoning
Process called "collect_latex_include" takes analyzer as Integer, include_element as Integer:
    If include_element is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    Let req_args be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with include_element, 24
    Let file_name be ""
    If req_args is not equal to 0:
        Let req_count be proc list_length from List with req_args
        If req_count is greater than 0:
            Let file_arg be proc list_get from List with req_args, 0
            Set file_name to proc extract_text_from_arg from Parser with file_arg
        End If
    End If
    Let includes be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 88
    proc add from List with includes, file_name
End Process

@Reasoning:
\input{file} inlines a file without a page break. Tracked in the inputs
list at offset 96; distinguished from \include so a dependency analyzer
can model the two TeX inclusion semantics correctly.
@End Reasoning
Process called "collect_latex_input" takes analyzer as Integer, input_element as Integer:
    If input_element is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    Let req_args be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with input_element, 24
    Let file_name be ""
    If req_args is not equal to 0:
        Let req_count be proc list_length from List with req_args
        If req_count is greater than 0:
            Let file_arg be proc list_get from List with req_args, 0
            Set file_name to proc extract_text_from_arg from Parser with file_arg
        End If
    End If
    Let inputs be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 96
    proc add from List with inputs, file_name
End Process

@Reasoning:
\includegraphics[opts]{file} records an embedded image. The graphics list
at offset 104 captures each so a build can verify the referenced asset
exists and that the graphicx package was loaded.
@End Reasoning
Process called "collect_latex_graphics" takes analyzer as Integer, graphics_element as Integer:
    If graphics_element is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    Let graphics be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 104
    proc add from List with graphics, graphics_element
End Process

@Reasoning:
Catch-all collector for body commands that are not one of the recognised
structural kinds. We register the command in the commands Dict (offset 16)
keyed by its name so the analyzer can report command-usage statistics and
detect uses of undefined user macros. Commands with no name are ignored.
@End Reasoning
Process called "collect_latex_command" takes analyzer as Integer, command_element as Integer:
    If command_element is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    Let node_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with command_element, 0
    If node_type is not equal to Parser.NODE_COMMAND:
        Return
    End If
    Let cmd_name be proc memory_get_pointer from Memory with command_element, 8
    If cmd_name is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    Let commands be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 16
    proc set from Dict with commands, cmd_name, command_element
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: STRUCTURE / PLACEMENT / PACKAGE VALIDATORS
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Class-specific structure rules. The book/report classes provide \chapter
while article does not; a document using \chapter under the article class
will fail to compile. We warn when the section list contains a chapter-
level entry (level 1) but the class is article/letter. This is a real
LaTeX correctness check, not a style preference.
@End Reasoning
Process called "validate_class_specific_structure" takes analyzer as Integer, class_name as Integer:
    If class_name is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let is_article be proc string_equals from StringCore with class_name, "article"
    Let is_letter be proc string_equals from StringCore with class_name, "letter"

    If is_article is equal to 0 and is_letter is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let sections be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 136
    Let section_count be proc size from List with sections
    Let index be 0

    While index is less than section_count:
        Let section be proc get from List with sections, index
        Let level be proc get_latex_section_level with section
        If level is equal to 1:
            Let warning be proc string_concat from StringPrim with "Chapter-level command used in class without chapters: ", class_name
            proc add_latex_validation_error with analyzer, warning
        End If
        Set index to index plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
A figure should carry a caption (academic convention) and ideally a label
(so it can be cross-referenced). We scan the figure environment body for a
\caption command and a \label; missing either yields a style warning. This
walks the real environment content list at offset 24.
@End Reasoning
Process called "validate_individual_figure" takes analyzer as Integer, figure as Integer:
    If figure is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    Let has_caption be proc environment_has_command with figure, "\\caption"
    If has_caption is equal to 0:
        proc add_latex_style_warning with analyzer, "Figure without a caption"
    End If
    Let label be proc find_label_in_environment with figure
    If label is equal to 0:
        proc add_latex_style_warning with analyzer, "Figure without a label - cannot be cross-referenced"
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Same caption/label expectations apply to tables. Walks the table
environment body for \caption and \label.
@End Reasoning
Process called "validate_individual_table" takes analyzer as Integer, table as Integer:
    If table is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    Let has_caption be proc environment_has_command with table, "\\caption"
    If has_caption is equal to 0:
        proc add_latex_style_warning with analyzer, "Table without a caption"
    End If
    Let label be proc find_label_in_environment with table
    If label is equal to 0:
        proc add_latex_style_warning with analyzer, "Table without a label - cannot be cross-referenced"
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Shared helper: scans an environment's body content list (offset 24) for a
named command node (e.g. "\caption"). Returns 1 on the first match, 0 if
none is found. Used by figure/table caption checks.
@End Reasoning
Process called "environment_has_command" takes env_element as Integer, command_name as Integer returns Integer:
    If env_element is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let content be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with env_element, 24
    If content is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let count be proc list_length from List with content
    Let index be 0
    While index is less than count:
        Let child be proc list_get from List with content, index
        Let child_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with child, 0
        If child_type is equal to Parser.NODE_COMMAND:
            Let child_name be proc memory_get_pointer from Memory with child, 8
            Let matches be proc string_equals from StringCore with child_name, command_name
            If matches is equal to 1:
                Return 1
            End If
        End If
        Set index to index plus 1
    End While
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Figure caption format check used by the academic-conventions phase. A
figure caption should be present; we reuse environment_has_command. The
separation from validate_individual_figure lets the caption convention be
reported under style rather than structure diagnostics.
@End Reasoning
Process called "validate_figure_caption_format" takes analyzer as Integer, figure as Integer:
    If figure is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    Let has_caption be proc environment_has_command with figure, "\\caption"
    If has_caption is equal to 0:
        proc add_latex_style_warning with analyzer, "Figure caption missing - add \\caption for list-of-figures"
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Table caption format check - the table counterpart to the figure caption
check.
@End Reasoning
Process called "validate_table_caption_format" takes analyzer as Integer, table as Integer:
    If table is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    Let has_caption be proc environment_has_command with table, "\\caption"
    If has_caption is equal to 0:
        proc add_latex_style_warning with analyzer, "Table caption missing - add \\caption for list-of-tables"
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Figure content validity: a figure environment that contains neither a
\includegraphics nor any tabular/text content is almost always an authoring
mistake (an empty float). We warn when the environment body is empty.
@End Reasoning
Process called "validate_latex_figure_content" takes analyzer as Integer, figure_element as Integer:
    If figure_element is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    Let content be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with figure_element, 24
    If content is equal to 0:
        proc add_latex_style_warning with analyzer, "Empty figure environment"
        Return
    End If
    Let count be proc list_length from List with content
    If count is equal to 0:
        proc add_latex_style_warning with analyzer, "Empty figure environment"
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Table structure validity: a table environment should contain a tabular (or
array) sub-environment to actually render rows. We scan for a nested
NODE_ENVIRONMENT; absence is flagged as a style warning because a table
float with no tabular produces no visible content.
@End Reasoning
Process called "validate_latex_table_structure" takes analyzer as Integer, table_element as Integer:
    If table_element is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    Let content be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with table_element, 24
    If content is equal to 0:
        proc add_latex_style_warning with analyzer, "Empty table environment - no tabular content"
        Return
    End If
    Let count be proc list_length from List with content
    Let has_tabular be 0
    Let index be 0
    While index is less than count:
        Let child be proc list_get from List with content, index
        Let child_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with child, 0
        If child_type is equal to Parser.NODE_ENVIRONMENT:
            Set has_tabular to 1
        End If
        Set index to index plus 1
    End While
    If has_tabular is equal to 0:
        proc add_latex_style_warning with analyzer, "Table environment without a tabular - no rows will render"
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Equation content validity: an equation environment with an empty body
produces a blank equation number, which is an authoring error. We warn on
empty equation content.
@End Reasoning
Process called "validate_latex_equation_content" takes analyzer as Integer, equation_element as Integer:
    If equation_element is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    Let content be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with equation_element, 24
    If content is equal to 0:
        proc add_latex_style_warning with analyzer, "Empty equation environment"
        Return
    End If
    Let count be proc list_length from List with content
    If count is equal to 0:
        proc add_latex_style_warning with analyzer, "Empty equation environment"
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Equation formatting convention: every display equation should be labelled
so it can be referenced with \eqref. We walk the analyzer's equation list
(offset 128) and warn for any equation that has no \label in its body.
@End Reasoning
Process called "validate_equation_formatting" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Let equations be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 128
    Let count be proc size from List with equations
    Let index be 0
    While index is less than count:
        Let equation be proc get from List with equations, index
        Let label be proc find_label_in_environment with equation
        If label is equal to 0:
            proc add_latex_style_warning with analyzer, "Unlabelled display equation - add \\label for cross-referencing"
        End If
        Set index to index plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Bibliography entry validity: a bibliography entry must have a non-empty
citation key, otherwise \cite can never resolve it. We flag empty-key
entries as validation errors.
@End Reasoning
Process called "validate_latex_bibliography_entry" takes analyzer as Integer, bibliography_element as Integer:
    If bibliography_element is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    Let key be proc get_latex_bibliography_key with bibliography_element
    Let key_len be proc string_length from StringCore with key
    If key_len is equal to 0:
        proc add_latex_validation_error with analyzer, "Bibliography entry with empty citation key"
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Bibliography formatting convention check: warns when the document cites
sources but registers no bibliography entries at all (a missing
\bibliography / \printbibliography), which yields [?] markers in the
output.
@End Reasoning
Process called "check_bibliography_formatting" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Let citations be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 48
    Let bibliography be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 56
    Let cite_count be proc size from List with citations
    Let bib_count be proc size from List with bibliography
    If cite_count is greater than 0 and bib_count is equal to 0:
        proc add_latex_validation_warning with analyzer, "Document has citations but no bibliography entries were found"
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
detect_undefined_references is the diagnostic-aggregation companion to
resolve_label_references. resolve_label_references already populated the
undefined_references list; this pass surfaces a single summary warning when
that list is non-empty so a caller scanning warnings (not the full error
list) still learns the document has broken cross-references.
@End Reasoning
Process called "detect_undefined_references" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Let undefined_references be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 160
    Let count be proc size from List with undefined_references
    If count is greater than 0:
        proc add_latex_validation_warning with analyzer, "Document contains undefined references"
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
validate_package_options walks every loaded package and checks for options
that conflict within a single \usepackage call. The common case is the
draft/final pair (mutually exclusive). We compare each package's option
string for both tokens and flag the contradiction.
@End Reasoning
Process called "validate_package_options" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Let packages be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 8
    Let count be proc size from List with packages
    Let index be 0
    While index is less than count:
        Let package be proc get from List with packages, index
        Let options be proc get_latex_package_options with package
        Let has_draft be proc string_index_of from StringPrim with options, "draft"
        Let has_final be proc string_index_of from StringPrim with options, "final"
        If has_draft is greater than 0 - 1 and has_final is greater than 0 - 1:
            proc add_latex_validation_error with analyzer, "Package loaded with conflicting draft and final options"
        End If
        Set index to index plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
check_required_packages verifies that constructs used in the document have
their enabling package loaded. The canonical case is \includegraphics
requiring graphicx; if any graphics were collected but graphicx is absent,
the document fails to compile. We check the graphics list (offset 104)
against the loaded package names.
@End Reasoning
Process called "check_required_packages" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Let graphics be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 104
    Let graphics_count be proc size from List with graphics
    If graphics_count is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let packages be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 8
    Let package_count be proc size from List with packages
    Let has_graphicx be 0
    Let index be 0
    While index is less than package_count:
        Let package be proc get from List with packages, index
        Let package_name be proc get_latex_package_name with package
        Let is_graphicx be proc string_equals from StringCore with package_name, "graphicx"
        If is_graphicx is equal to 1:
            Set has_graphicx to 1
        End If
        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    If has_graphicx is equal to 0:
        proc add_latex_validation_error with analyzer, "Document uses \\includegraphics but graphicx package is not loaded"
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Verifies that "early" packages (inputenc, fontenc, babel) are loaded
before any other package. These encoding/language packages must come first
or character handling breaks. We find the index of the first non-early
package and warn for any early package that appears after it.
@End Reasoning
Process called "validate_early_package_order" takes analyzer as Integer, packages as Integer, early_packages as Integer:
    Let package_count be proc size from List with packages
    Let first_non_early be 0 - 1
    Let index be 0

    While index is less than package_count:
        Let package be proc get from List with packages, index
        Let package_name be proc get_latex_package_name with package
        Let is_early be proc package_list_contains with early_packages, package_name

        If is_early is equal to 0:
            If first_non_early is equal to 0 - 1:
                Set first_non_early to index
            End If
        Otherwise:
            If first_non_early is greater than 0 - 1:
                Let warning be proc string_concat from StringPrim with "Encoding/language package should load earlier: ", package_name
                proc add_latex_validation_warning with analyzer, warning
            End If
        End If

        Set index to index plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Verifies that "late" packages (hyperref, cleveref) are loaded after all
others. hyperref in particular patches many commands and must come last.
We find the last late-package index and warn for any non-late package that
appears after it.
@End Reasoning
Process called "validate_late_package_order" takes analyzer as Integer, packages as Integer, late_packages as Integer:
    Let package_count be proc size from List with packages
    Let last_late be 0 - 1
    Let index be 0

    While index is less than package_count:
        Let package be proc get from List with packages, index
        Let package_name be proc get_latex_package_name with package
        Let is_late be proc package_list_contains with late_packages, package_name
        If is_late is equal to 1:
            Set last_late to index
        End If
        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    If last_late is equal to 0 - 1:
        Return
    End If

    Let after be last_late plus 1
    While after is less than package_count:
        Let pkg be proc get from List with packages, after
        Let pkg_name be proc get_latex_package_name with pkg
        Let pkg_is_late be proc package_list_contains with late_packages, pkg_name
        If pkg_is_late is equal to 0:
            Let warning be proc string_concat from StringPrim with "Package loads after hyperref/cleveref and may break: ", pkg_name
            proc add_latex_validation_warning with analyzer, warning
        End If
        Set after to after plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Reports a conflict when both packages of a known-incompatible pair are
present in the loaded-package name list. Used by detect_package_conflicts
for pairs like amsmath/amstex and natbib/biblatex.
@End Reasoning
Process called "check_conflicting_package_pair" takes analyzer as Integer, loaded_packages as Integer, package_a as Integer, package_b as Integer:
    Let has_a be proc package_list_contains with loaded_packages, package_a
    Let has_b be proc package_list_contains with loaded_packages, package_b
    If has_a is equal to 1 and has_b is equal to 1:
        Let error be proc string_concat from StringPrim with "Conflicting packages loaded together: ", package_a
        Let error2 be proc string_concat from StringPrim with error, " and "
        Let error3 be proc string_concat from StringPrim with error2, package_b
        proc add_latex_validation_error with analyzer, error3
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Returns 1 if the given package name appears in a list of package-name
strings, 0 otherwise. Linear scan with string_equals - the package lists
are short (a handful of entries) so no hashing is warranted.
@End Reasoning
Process called "package_list_contains" takes package_list as Integer, package_name as Integer returns Integer:
    If package_list is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let count be proc size from List with package_list
    Let index be 0
    While index is less than count:
        Let entry be proc get from List with package_list, index
        Let matches be proc string_equals from StringCore with entry, package_name
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
        Set index to index plus 1
    End While
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Builds the set of loaded package names from the analyzer's package list
(offset 8). Returned as a fresh List of name strings so callers
(check_latex_package_conflicts) can run package_list_contains against it
without re-extracting names on every query.
@End Reasoning
Process called "get_loaded_packages" takes analyzer as Integer returns Integer:
    Let result be proc create from List
    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return result
    End If
    Let packages be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 8
    Let count be proc size from List with packages
    Let index be 0
    While index is less than count:
        Let package be proc get from List with packages, index
        Let package_name be proc get_latex_package_name with package
        proc add from List with result, package_name
        Set index to index plus 1
    End While
    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
Classifies the citation commands seen in the document into style families
and returns a Dict keyed by style name ("numeric" for \cite, "authoryear"
for \citet/\citep, "biblatex" for \textcite/\parencite). A document mixing
families produces a multi-key dict, which validate_citation_style treats as
a consistency warning. Returns the populated style dict.
@End Reasoning
Process called "analyze_citation_patterns" takes citations as Integer returns Integer:
    Let styles be proc create from Dict
    If citations is equal to 0:
        Return styles
    End If
    Let count be proc size from List with citations
    Let index be 0
    While index is less than count:
        Let citation be proc get from List with citations, index
        Let node_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with citation, 0

        Note:
        A NODE_CITATION came from the dedicated \cite token (numeric style).
        Citation variants parsed as generic commands carry their name at
        offset 8 and are classified by that name.
        :End Note
        If node_type is equal to Parser.NODE_CITATION:
            proc set from Dict with styles, "numeric", 1
        Otherwise:
            If node_type is equal to Parser.NODE_COMMAND:
                Let cmd_name be proc memory_get_pointer from Memory with citation, 8
                Let is_citet be proc string_equals from StringCore with cmd_name, "\\citet"
                Let is_citep be proc string_equals from StringCore with cmd_name, "\\citep"
                Let is_textcite be proc string_equals from StringCore with cmd_name, "\\textcite"
                Let is_parencite be proc string_equals from StringCore with cmd_name, "\\parencite"
                If is_citet is equal to 1 or is_citep is equal to 1:
                    proc set from Dict with styles, "authoryear", 1
                End If
                If is_textcite is equal to 1 or is_parencite is equal to 1:
                    proc set from Dict with styles, "biblatex", 1
                End If
            End If
        End If

        Set index to index plus 1
    End While
    Return styles
End Process

@Reasoning:
check_document_completeness verifies the document has the minimum elements
expected of a finished academic document: at least one section and (when
the document defines floats) at least one piece of body content. A
sectionless document is flagged as a style warning since it is almost
always an incomplete draft.
@End Reasoning
Process called "check_document_completeness" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Let sections be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 136
    Let document_structure be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 144
    Let section_count be proc size from List with sections
    Let structure_count be proc size from List with document_structure

    If section_count is equal to 0 and structure_count is equal to 0:
        proc add_latex_style_warning with analyzer, "Document body has no structural elements - appears incomplete"
    End If
End Process